    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1875-02-21T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1875-02-21T00:00:00-05:00" n="72" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d72">
                <head>No. 68.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Partridge</persName> to Mr. <persName type="to">Fish</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">United
                                    States Legation</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Rio de
                                Janeiro</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1875-02-21">
                            <hi rend="italic">February</hi> 21, 1875</date>.
                            (Received March 23.)</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 234.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: It would appear from the accounts we have from
                        Buenos Ayres that, as soon as the late revolution there was suppressed, that
                        government has again turned its attention to the arming and fortifying of
                        the island of Martin Garcia.</p>
                <p>This fact causes uneasiness here; and, if this design is persisted in, it
                        will certainly cause unfriendly feelings, and possibly hostility, on the
                        part of Brazil.</p>
                <p>In communications from this legation numbered 147 and 148,<note n="*" xml:id="d72fn1">See <ref target="frus1874#pg_73">Foreign Relations for
                                1874, pages 73</ref> and <ref target="frus1874#pg_75">75</ref>.</note> this matter has already been explained to the
                        Department; and the continuation of military works on, or occupation of that
                        island by the Argentines can only mean that the party now in power there
                        mean to provoke hostilities with this country.</p>
                <p rend="center">* * * * * * *</p>
                <p>I am, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>JAMES R. PARTRIDGE.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
